Small and inconspicuous Trinidadian (West Indian) take out restaurant that serves homemade traditional Trinidadian Indian dishes. They take Indian heritage dishes and have given it a variant twist to them by playing with the traditional spices from India as well as ingredients the immigrants found on the island when they arrived there over a century and a half ago.  The duck curry was not as soft and tender as it should have been. The shrimp curry fared better, but it too could have been more marinated before being infused into the curry base.  Service was friendly as it was helmed by two beautiful young ladies. The namesake proprietor,  Jenny, was engaging and had a  larger-than-life persona.  It seems they have grown into a local staple in the neighborhood.

I’m not one to leave reviews. But after the experience had I feel I have to. Last week after work I called to order dhal puri this was at 610pm. I picked up at 630pm and went home 3 blocks away. I purchased 4 It smelled weIrd in the car but that’s normal because of the bag they put it in. Like most I feed my son because eating he refused to eat and I found something else to feed him and then it was my turn. From the first piece the taste was off think it might have been the curry. I took another piece and eat that by itself but it was clear the dhal filling was spoiled. The dough was fine but the filling was spoil took the next one out and it was the same across all 4. I’m not as mad at the money lost but at the quality of the food. If my son had actually eat this I would have definitely report them. But reading reviews I hope this message gets to the owner and they can make the adjustments for better quality food . We strongly need a decent West Indian restaurant within our community.
